      <section eId="section_2">
        <heading>Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act</b><br /><b>DBT Impact Assessment</b><br /><b>September 2024</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>Contents</b></p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_3">
        <heading>Overview</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Overview</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>1.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>This document presents the Impact Assessment for DBT, formerly BEIS, measures within the Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act. Impact Assessments from other departments, including the Home Office, the Ministry of Justice, and Her Majesty’s Treasury were published alongside the Bill’s introduction.<authorialNote marker="1"><p> Overarching Home Office Impact Assessment reference is HO0413</p></authorialNote> The two final stage Impact Assessments for the DBT measures are:</p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Corporate Transparency and Companies House Register Reform</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p>Limited Partnerships: Reform of Limited Partnership Law</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>2.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act will: prevent misuse of UK registered entities, including limited partnerships, improve the accuracy of information held at Companies House, give additional powers to seize crypto-assets more quickly and easily, and give businesses more confidence to share information in order to tackle money laundering and other economic crime. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_4">
        <heading>Background</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Background</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>3.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Recent years have seen growing instances of misuse of companies, concerns over the accuracy of the companies register and challenges safeguarding personal data on the register. In parallel, several stakeholders have drawn attention to the opportunity for Companies House to play a greater role tackling economic crime, working in partnership with other agencies and the private sector. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>4.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The Corporate Transparency and Register Reform White Paper, published in February 2022, builds on the consultation responses received in both 2019 and 2020.<authorialNote marker="2"><p> See: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/corporate-transparency-and-register-reform"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/corporate-transparency-and-register-reform</u></a> </p></authorialNote> This set out the Government’s position ahead of introducing these reforms into Parliament. An Impact Assessment was published alongside the White Paper providing stakeholders with an initial assessment of the costs and benefits of this policy.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_5">
        <heading>Focus of this document</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Focus of this document</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>5.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Corporate Transparency and Companies House Register Reform</b>: The Act will reform the role of Companies House and improve transparency over UK companies and property, in order to strengthen our business environment, support our national security and combat economic crime, whilst delivering a more reliable companies register to underpin business activity.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>6.</num>
          <content>
            <p><b>Amendments made during Bill’s passage: </b>The Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act received Royal Assent in October 2023.<authorialNote marker="3"><p> See: <a href="https://bills.parliament.uk/bills/3339"><u>https://bills.parliament.uk/bills/3339</u></a> </p></authorialNote> Throughout the Bill’s passage through Parliament, various amendments were made to the legislation. Following our assessment of these amendments, we <u>do not</u> believe that the primary legislation has been amended in such a way that significantly changes the impacts set out in this IA. <u>As a result, a full enactment Impact Assessment has not been produced</u>.<i> </i>It is possible that as a result of further work on secondary legislation or during Companies House implementation that our assessment of costs and benefits will change. This will be reflected in any Impact Assessments accompanying regulations.</p>
