      <section eId="section_139">
        <heading>Conclusion</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Conclusion</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>423.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We conclude that the measure should have no adverse or disproportionate negative impact on persons or groups with a protected characteristic and no steps need to be taken to advance equality of opportunity and foster good relations because of or in relation to them.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>424.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The measures under this proposal are not expected to give rise to discrimination, harassment, victimisation, or any other conduct prohibited by or under the Equality Act 2010.  Further, they do not make specific or direct provision in respect of any of the protected characteristics, and they are not expected to result in outcomes where people who share particular protected characteristics are treated differently from people who do not. They are not expected to give rise to a direct or indirect impact on individuals because of any protected characteristic they may have.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>425.</num>
          <content>
            <p>On this basis, we do not consider it is necessary or proportionate to seek further evidence to support this assessment, or to recommend any changes to our existing plans. The department does not intend to monitor in relation to Public Sector Equality Duty specifically, but the department is required to carry out a Post-Implementation Review of the measure five years after it comes into force.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_140">
        <heading>Competition and innovation impact test</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b><u>Competition and innovation impact test</u></b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>426.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The proposed reforms affect all companies across sectors, and we thus have not identified any specific competition and innovation impacts. The proposals will help strengthen the position and protect consumers and businesses who ‘do the right thing’ from those who aim to abuse the current corporate framework.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>427.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The 2018 BEIS commissioned research on the value of the companies register found that of the businesses surveyed, 86% used company information to confirm basic information about a company, 71% to carry out due diligence work about a company and 28% to check risk/creditworthiness of a supplier. By having more up to date, accurate data on the companies register it should support business when transacting with one another and thus promote competitive business taking place. Similarly, having more reliable and trustworthy data on the companies register should support business and thus have a positive impact on innovation.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_141">
        <heading>A summary of the potential trade implications of measures</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b><u>A summary of the potential trade implications of measures</u></b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>428.</num>
          <content>
            <p>There are 12,475 companies incorporated outside of the United Kingdom currently registered at Companies House and approximately 58,592 companies with another company as its Global Ultimate Owner of the United Kingdom.<authorialNote marker="140"><p> See: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/companies-register-activities-statistical-release-2020-to-2021"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/companies-register-activities-statistical-release-2020-to-2021</u></a> and analysis of the FAME database. </p></authorialNote></p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>429.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We do not envisage any implications of trade due to these measures. Improving company regulation should signal that the UK as a good place to invest and set up a company. It should also provide greater confidence to foreign entities that the UK companies they trade with are legitimate. Even with the increased requirements due to these reforms, it will remain relatively quick and low cost to set up a company in the UK.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_142">
        <heading>Environmental impacts</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b><u>Environmental impacts</u></b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>430.</num>
          <content>
            <p>There are no obvious direct concerns in this area. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_143">
        <heading>Human rights</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b><u>Human rights</u></b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>431.</num>
          <content>
            <p>By allowing greater scrutiny of companies that are engaging in illicit activities these measures could have an indirect effect on human rights. For example, by reducing the attractiveness of companies as vehicles for money laundering, which is linked to other serious crimes such as people trafficking.  </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_144">
        <heading>Justice system</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b><u>Justice system</u></b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>432.</num>
          <content>
            <p>A Justice Impact Test (JIT) is the Ministry of Justice tool that helps policymakers across government find the best way of achieving their policy aims whilst minimising the impact on the justice system. A JIT has been submitted to the Ministry of Justice.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_145">
        <heading>Impact on small and micro businesses</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b><u>Impact on small and micro businesses</u></b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>433.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The measures in this reform package will impact small and micro business. Most companies registered with Companies House are small or micro (estimated to be around 90%). </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>434.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Overall, introducing exemptions based on company size would undermine the objectives of this policy. For example, if small and micro businesses did not have to verify the identities of its directors or PSCs, this could be a loophole that criminals could exploit. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>435.</num>
          <content>
            <p>From a per entity perspective, the burdens on small and micro businesses are likely to be lower. For example, they are more likely to have fewer directors and PSCs who will need to be identity verified than a large company with many directors, and likely to be easier to contact to do this.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>436.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Regarding reforming accounts, any evidence for disproportionate impacts is limited. On the contrary, we have investigated random samples of companies that currently file on paper with Companies House, and this did not indicate that these companies are more likely to be small. If anything, our current evidence, and experience suggests that these companies are larger on average, meaning that we do currently not expect a disproportionate impact on small companies from the proposals to mandate electronic filing of accounts.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>437.</num>
          <content>
            <p>It could also be argued that a more transparent and accurate companies register will be particularly beneficial to small and micro businesses, as they are arguably more likely to rely on Companies House data as a key source of due diligence compared to larger companies who may have the resource to undertake more rigorous checks. The valuing the user benefits of Companies House data asked direct users of the data their annual expenditure on additional company information and data products, of which 18% of respondents answered yes.<authorialNote marker="141"><p> See: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/companies-house-data-valuing-the-user-benefits"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/companies-house-data-valuing-the-user-benefits</u></a> </p></authorialNote> The costs of these additional data products had a mean of £1,640. This reiterates the value in having free, high-quality data available for small and micro businesses.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>438.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We know that small and micro businesses place a high value on being able to incorporate. Recent published research from BEIS found that the total value of company incorporation to owners of Limited Liability Companies with 0 to 9 employees in the UK is estimated to be approximately £9.6 billion per year.<authorialNote marker="142"><p> See: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/understanding-the-reasons-for-forming-a-company"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/understanding-the-reasons-for-forming-a-company</u></a> </p></authorialNote> Overall, the study shows that the choice to incorporate is not solely based on financial or administrative burden factors that are within the direct control of business regulation and policymaking. Whilst these factors do matter and at the margin changes in incorporation fee, tax liability, and administrative requirements will impact LLC business formation, a richer set of influences also matter and in some cases are more material to business owners than the direct policy levers.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>439.</num>
          <content>
            <p>In terms of mitigations, Companies House will work with the small and micro business community to ensure they understand what they need to do to be compliant with these policy changes - for example, through guidance that is relevant and accessible.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num><b>VIII.</b></num>
          <content>
            <p />
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num><b>IX.</b></num>
          <content>
            <p><b>     Monitoring and evaluation</b></p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>440.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The department, working with Companies House, will monitor the impacts following these reforms. This includes monitoring some of the key metrics available, such as number of incorporations, dissolutions, and the frequency with which Companies House data is accessed.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>441.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Overall, the transformation of Companies House and the measures set out in this reform package will increase our ability to better explore its data will enable us to understand the impact of these policy proposals.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>442.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We have outlined throughout the Impact Assessment that some of the details of this policy are still being developed and thus the challenges of accurately quantifying the impacts given the primary legislative stage of this assessment. To mitigate this, we have explored a range of costs and outlined that we will continue to build upon this throughout secondary stage and within Post-Implementation Reviews. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_146">
        <heading>Costs to business of the proposals</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b><u>Costs to business of the proposals</u></b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>443.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We will monitor and evaluate whether the costs to business estimated were reflective of the impact on business. We will continue to engage with key stakeholders to do this as well as analyse Companies House data e.g. the number of identity verifications, to review our estimates of the current stock and future flow of individuals on the register.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_147">
        <heading>Benefits to business of the proposals</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b><u>Benefits to business of the proposals</u></b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>444.</num>
          <content>
            <p>As outlined in part<b> V</b> the key benefits are better quality data to support enterprise and supporting the prevention of economic crime.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>445.</num>
          <content>
            <p>On supporting enterprise, we are likely to repeat the externally commissioned research valuing the data on the company data, which was valued at between £1-3 billion a year. This would test whether the value of the data has increased and include whether identity verification had increased the value of the data. Something to note here is that, to look at willingness-to-pay overtime, you want to change as little as possible within the surveys. This could be overcome if the study was re-run with a split sample. Some respondents would get the original study “package”, some respondents would get the new package including identity verification information. That would allow for (a) comparing values over time for any change and (b) understanding the added value of the higher quality data. An increase in the value of this data, due to the changes seen in this policy package, could be seen as a measure of success of this policy.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>446.</num>
          <content>
            <p>On the prevention of economic crime, we will work with stakeholders, particularly law enforcement on whether the proposals have supported the prevention of economic crime. There are challenges with accurately quantifying the impact of economic crime and within our monitoring and evaluation we will actively explore different approaches to quantify the benefits of these reforms in preventing, or helping to fight, economic crime. Some of the proposals themselves, such as increased data sharing, will enable us to develop a greater understanding of this.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_148">
        <heading>Annex Amendments made during Bill passage</heading>
        <content>
          <p><b>Annex: Amendments made during Bill passage</b></p>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_149">
        <heading>Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act</heading>
        <content>
          <p><b>Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act</b></p>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_150">
        <heading>Summary of Amendments made to DBT Measures</heading>
        <content>
          <p><b>Summary of Amendments made to DBT Measures</b></p>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_151">
        <heading>September 2024</heading>
        <content>
          <p><b>September 2024</b></p>
        </content>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_152">
        <heading>Background</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Background</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>1.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act received Royal Assent in October 2023.<authorialNote marker="143"><p> See: <a href="https://bills.parliament.uk/bills/3339"><u>https://bills.parliament.uk/bills/3339</u></a> </p></authorialNote> The Act gives powers to make significant reforms to Companies House and increases transparency of UK companies. It aims to: prevent the misuse of UK registered entities (including limited partnerships), improve the accuracy of information held at Companies House and provide additional powers to seize crypto assets quicker and easier.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>2.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Overall, the role of the Act is to strengthen the UK’s response to economic crime through preventing the misuse of UK registered entities in illicit activities and improving the reliability of the data available on the companies register.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>3.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>Two final stage Impact Assessments for the Department for Business and Trade’s (DBT) measures, were published at the Act’s introduction:<authorialNote marker="144"><p> See: <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/2023/56/contents"><u>Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act 2023 (legislation.gov.uk)</u></a></p></authorialNote></p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <intro>
              <p><b>Corporate Transparency and Companies House Register Reform: </b></p>
            </intro>
            <subparagraph>
              <content>
                <p>Introduce identity verification, widen Companies House powers to query/investigate information they receive and improve the quality of information available to users of the register. The net cost to business per year was assessed at £18.9m (2023 base year, 2019 prices). Around 80% of these costs were due to the introduction of identity verification, as it will impact almost 7 million individuals already on the register.</p>
              </content>
            </subparagraph>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><b>Reform of Limited Partnership Law:</b> Tighten registration requirements, require limited partnerships to demonstrate a firmer connection to the UK, increase transparency requirements and enable the Registrar to strike from the register limited partnerships which are dissolved or which are no longer carrying on business. The net cost to business per year was assessed at £2.2m (2023 base year, 2019 prices).</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>4.</num>
          <content>
            <p class="ia-title">Impact Assessments from other departments, including the Home Office, the Ministry of Justice, and His Majesty’s Treasury were published alongside this at the Bill’s introduction.<authorialNote marker="145"><p> See: <a href="https://bills.parliament.uk/bills/3339/publications"><u>https://bills.parliament.uk/bills/3339/publications</u></a> </p><p>Overarching Home Office Impact Assessment reference is HO0413</p></authorialNote></p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_153">
        <heading>Focus of this document</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Focus of this document </b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>5.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Throughout the Bill’s passage through Parliament, various amendments were made to the legislation. As per the Better Regulation Framework: <i>“Enactment IAs are required only for primary legislation that has been amended in its passage through Parliament in such a way as to significantly change the impacts of the policy on business […] If the impacts of the Act remain unchanged then an enactment IA is not necessary.”</i> <authorialNote marker="146"><p> See: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/better-regulation-framework"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/better-regulation-framework</u></a></p></authorialNote></p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>6.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Following our assessment of these amendments, we <u>do not</u> believe that the primary legislation has been amended in such a way that significantly changes the impacts of the policy on business. <u>As a result, </u><i><u>a full enactment Impact Assessment has not been produced</u></i><i>. </i>It is possible that as a result of further work on secondary legislation or during Companies House implementation that our assessment of costs and benefits will change. This will be reflected in any Impact Assessments accompanying regulations.  </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>7.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Summarised below are all of the amendments (with respect to DBT’s measures) made at each stage of the Bill’s passage through Parliament, as well as the supporting cost assessment for each:</p>
            <table uk:widths="3.15in 3.93in">
              <tr>
                <td colspan="2">
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Commons Committee and Report Stage Amendments</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Amendment</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Cost Assessment on Business</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">A small number of minor and technical amendments to address drafting deficiencies</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text" />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">A small number of minor and technical amendments to address drafting deficiencies and complete the legislation. For instance, replacing references to ‘companies’ with ‘body corporate’.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">These amendments were only used to complete the existing legislation and pose no direct cost to business.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments needed to align the Register of Overseas Entities with Companies House reform and to better implement the Register of Overseas Entities.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">As far as possible, the requirements of the Register of Overseas Entities mirror the equivalent requirements for the Persons with Significant Control of UK companies. Where ‘mirrored’ provisions are changing as a result of Companies House reform, we will assess whether an equivalent change is required to the Register of Overseas Entities. Any differences in approach will reflect the different requirements on overseas entities compared with UK companies.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">These may pose a very small additional cost to each overseas business in scope, but overall costs are unlikely to be significant given the share of entities affected by this amendment – ~31,000 overseas entities vs. 4.9 million companies.<authorialNote marker="147"><p class="ia-table-text"> Companies register activities (Statistical release April 2023 to March 2024): <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/companies-register-activities-statistical-release-april-2023-to-march-2024"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/companies-register-activities-statistical-release-april-2023-to-march-2024</u></a> </p></authorialNote></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Introducing a requirement for the Government to publish an annual report on implementation of Companies House Reforms.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Publishing an annual report is a cost to government and will not directly impact business.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Removal of some of the identity verification exemptions for directors</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment removed a regulation making power that could be used to exempt categories of directors from identity verification requirements as the power was assessed as being unlikely to be used, and therefore removed from the Act. This has no cost impact on businesses. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Requirements relating to the dissolution, revival, deregistration, winding up and sequestration of limited partnerships </p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This will allow limited partnerships (LPs) that are both solvent and insolvent to be:</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• dissolved, </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• wound up on petition to the High Court or Court of Session (if registered in Scotland), </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• sequestrated (if registered in Scotland), </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• administratively revived to the register, </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• deregistered, </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• removed from the index of names held by the registrar</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Internal analysis suggests there are only 18,000 <u>active</u> LPs.<authorialNote marker="148"><p class="ia-table-text"> Whilst There are roughly 58,000 Limited Partnerships on the register, this also includes limited partnerships that are closed as they have not been removed from the register. We have done some further analysis to estimate the share of these entities that are active. See the methodology used here: The Registrar (Identity Verification and Authorised Corporate Service Providers) Regulations 2024 pg. 24: <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukdsi/2024/9780348261905/impacts/2024/96"><u>https://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukdsi/2024/9780348261905/impacts/2024/96</u></a> </p></authorialNote> Any LPs that are solvent are making a choice to dissolve and can most likely bear any costs involved. LPs that are insolvent are most likely being dissolved or wound up due to non-compliance. Any costs incurred from non-compliance would fall out of scope of our analysis. As a result, we assess no direct cost to business.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Strengthening the range of sanctions for non-compliance with the Register of Overseas Entities</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment includes the following:</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• Enforcement of requirement to register: updated language about penalties etc</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text" />
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• Financial penalties: interaction with offences</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">These amendments will only directly impact businesses who have been sanctioned due to non-compliance. Therefore, we do not consider it within our cost assessment. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
            <table uk:widths="3.15in 3.93in">
              <tr>
                <td colspan="2">
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Lords Committee Stage Amendments</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Amendment</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Cost Assessment on Business</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to strengthen the Registrar’s objectives (e.g. the new role of the company registrar) and power to require information</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment provides the registrar with more power to query/challenge information. The vast majority of companies burdened by this would be those which have chosen to file incorrect information on purpose or even with criminal intent and therefore out of scope of our analysis.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Any costs incurred from non-compliance are not considered in our cost assessment.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to strengthen shareholder transparency</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment provides a more effective legal framework for companies/members to follow. </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">These amendments included the following:</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">a) New powers allowing companies to obtain information from their members and ensure it is kept up to date, and new duties for members to provide this information and keep it up to date</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">b) New offences for members and companies who fail to do so without a reasonable excuse</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">c) New power for the Secretary of State to make regulations to allow people to apply to “protect” information from being publicly available in the company’s register of members </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">A comprehensive assessment will be undertaken if the Government chose to exercise this power. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to address interplays between director disqualification measures and the sanctions regime</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment achieved the following:</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• Created a new type of sanction in the Sanctions and Anti-Money Laundering Act 2018 called director disqualification sanctions.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">• Ensured consistency between Great Britain and Northern Ireland legislation regarding director disqualification sanctions measure.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment will impact individuals who have been disqualified for failing to comply with requirements. Any costs which arise would be from non-compliance, which we do not consider when assessing the cost to businesses.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to extend the application of company director disqualification provisions to other entities in Northern Ireland</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text" />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Provided powers to make regulations to amend the Company Directors Disqualification Act 1986 and the Company Directors Disqualification (Northern Ireland) Order 2002. The regulations will widen the scope of the legislation to apply to other relevant entities, such as limited partnerships.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Costs will only arise as a result of non-compliance and, as a result fall out of scope of our analysis.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments addressing the interaction between the disqualification regime and general partners/registered officers in limited partnerships</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This extends the disqualification regime to general partners and registered officers of limited partnerships.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Any costs which arise would be from non-compliance, which we do not consider when assessing the cost to businesses.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to the Register of Overseas entities, including the power to amend the Economic Crime (Transparency and Enforcement) Act 2022 in line with amendments to the Companies Act 2006, an amendment to the verification process, and introducing an anti-avoidance measure to capture changes in beneficial ownership from 28 February 2022 to registration or the end of the transitional period.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Overseas entities that sell properties or make any other disposition of land in scope of the Register of Overseas Entities (ROE) requirements (such as leases or charges) between 28 February 2022 and either their application for registration or the end of the transitional period, are obligated to submit their beneficial ownership details as at the point of disposition, along with details of the relevant properties. </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Businesses may incur a cost, however this is unlikely to be very burdensome. Ultimately, overseas entities only represent a small subset of the entire business population (31,000 overseas entities vs. 4.9 million companies), therefore the cost of this amendment will be minimal overall.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">The verification process for ROE may be amended. The details of this will be outlined in secondary legislation. We will consider whether this will lead to a significant change in our original cost estimates at this time.  </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
            <table uk:widths="3.15in 3.93in">
              <tr>
                <td colspan="2">
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Lords Report Stage Amendments</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Amendment</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Cost Assessment on Business</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">A new power providing scope to make regulations enabling the Registrar to prevent information from the profit and loss accounts of small companies and micro-entities being made available for public inspection</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">The power could be used to withhold all information from all profit and loss accounts from the public register, some information for all profit and loss accounts, or some information from the profit and loss accounts of some companies. It could also be implemented on application or automatically. The combination chosen, if the power is used at all, will ultimately impact the cost of implementation. </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Due to this uncertainty surrounding implementation and the lack of relevant evidence, we cannot assess the possible cost on business. We will look at updating this analysis if this power is ultimately used. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments related to Authorised Corporate Service Providers (ACSPs) and those who are to have authority to deliver documents to the Registrar.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">In combination these amendments:</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">1. Permitted verification statements delivered by ACSPs to confirm they have verified their client’s identity to be published on the register. The verification statement will include the name of the ACSPs and their supervisory authority. </p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">2. Clarified that regulations could be made to allow the Registrar to require information from ACSPs relating to identity verification checks</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">3. Restricted who could file information with Companies House to prevent unauthorised corporate service providers from being able to file, and</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">4. Introduced a ‘negative fit and proper person’ test as part of the authorisation process for ACSPs.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">1, 2 and 4 do not have an additional regulatory cost to business as they will be delivered by Companies House. 3 may have a cost to businesses or ACSPs who need to change their employment or company arrangements in order to use the current filing gateways. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to the director disqualification sanction regime and financial penalties.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment clarified when a person subject to director disqualification sanctions, or a person acting on the instructions of such an individual, is responsible for the debts of a company. The Department for the Economy in Northern Ireland will be required to maintain information about individuals subject to the new director disqualification sanctions in the Department’s register of disqualified directors. This mirrors the requirement for the Secretary of State to update the UK-wide Director Disqualification Register ensuring consistency between GB and NI legislation.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Where a person commits an offence, they may have either a financial penalty imposed upon them or be prosecuted criminally. Costs only apply to businesses which are non-compliant, which is outside of the scope for our cost assessment.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to increase access to information on overseas ownership of property via trusts, to further improve the transparency of the Register of Overseas Entities</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment introduced a new power for the Secretary of State to make regulations that set out the criteria under which the Registrar is required, on successful application, to disclose ROE trusts information. As the information is already collected, this will not directly have any costs to business. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to require more information to be provided about trust beneficiaries when an overseas entity submits an annual update, or a removal application to the Register of Overseas Entities.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment requires an overseas entity that has a beneficial owner, who is a trustee, to provide information about in-year changes to trust beneficiaries during the update period - instead of only providing a snapshot of the beneficiaries of the trust at the time that the update is made.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Businesses may incur a cost, however any costs are likely to be minimal. Much of this information is already held by these entities, therefore gathering and/or submitting this information is unlikely to pose significant additional burden.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
            <table uk:widths="3.15in 3.93in">
              <tr>
                <td colspan="2">
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Lords Third Reading Amendments</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Amendment</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Cost Assessment on Business</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to require companies to collect additional information about their PSCs</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Currently, a company must keep a local PSC register <i>and</i> provide the information contained within it to Companies House. The requirements to keep a local PSC register have been removed as part of the Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act 2023, so a company will only have to provide this information to Companies House. There have also been several amendments to the way in which companies determine who their PSCs are and how the notify Companies House.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment will apply to all companies and therefore will impact almost 5 million companies.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">The primary cost comes from these entities needing to familiarise themselves with this policy change. We assess a cost of £8.40 per entity - £40.3m for all 4.8 million entities. However, if every company were to save <u>at least</u> £0.84 per year from no longer holding a local register, over a 10-year appraisal period they would recoup their initial cost.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><i><u>Refer to the Appendix A for further details of this cost assessment.</u></i></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to align the drafting of false statement offences relating to the PSCs of UK companies with other similar offences in the ECCT Act 23</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment will impact those who have submitted a false statement. Therefore, costs only apply to businesses which are non-compliant and outside of our scope of cost to business.</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Amendments to close a gap by which the requirements of the Register of Overseas Entities can be circumvented by the use of a nominee arrangement.</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">The new provision requires that where an overseas entity holds land in the UK for another person in its capacity as a nominee, the other person is to be treated as a registrable beneficial owner of the nominee, thereby requiring the provision of information about them. Thereby closing the gap where those using the services of a nominee to hold land in the UK could avoid having their details disclosed to Companies House. It’s possible some costs may arise for businesses (i.e. gathering/ providing information on a nominee). However, this amendment only affects a small proportion of the company population (31,000 overseas entities vs. 4.9 million companies registered with Companies House) so any costs that do arise are likely to be minimal overall. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
            <table uk:widths="3.15in 3.93in">
              <tr>
                <td colspan="2">
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Lords Consideration of Commons Amendments Round 1 (LCCA1) Amendment</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Amendment</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Cost Assessment on Business</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">A new power to impose further duties involving nominee shareholders</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">This amendment allows the Secretary of State to make regulations to make further provision for the purpose of enabling a company to find out who its Persons of Significant Control are in cases where shares are held by a nominee. This could include, amongst other things: imposing further obligations on companies to find out if they have nominee shareholders, and if so, for whom they are holding shares; or imposing further obligations on nominee shareholders to disclose their status, and for whom they are holding shares.</p>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">Further details are required to undertake a comprehensive cost assessment alongside subsequent secondary legislation. </p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <level>
          <content>
            <p><b><u>Appendix A: </u></b><b><u>Amendments to require companies to collect additional information about their PSCs</u></b></p>
          </content>
        </level>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_154">
        <heading>Background</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Background</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>1.</num>
          <content>
            <p>The PSC register is a register of beneficial owners of UK companies. It was launched in 2016 following the introduction through the Small Business, Enterprise and Employment Act 2015 which amended the Companies Act 2006. The information on the register is publicly accessible and free of charge. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>2.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Currently, a company must keep a local PSC register <i>and</i> provide the information contained within it to Companies House. The requirements to keep a local PSC register have been removed as part of the Economic Crime and Corporate Transparency Act 2023, so a company will only have to provide this information to Companies House. There have also been several amendments to the way in which companies determine who their PSCs are and how the notify Companies House.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_155">
        <heading>Costs</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Costs</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>3.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Since this amendment will apply to all companies, all directors must familiarise themselves with the policy change. At the end of December 2023, there were 4.8 million on the effective register.<authorialNote marker="149"><p> See: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/incorporated-companies-in-the-uk-october-to-december-2023/incorporated-companies-in-the-uk-october-to-december-2023"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/incorporated-companies-in-the-uk-october-to-december-2023/incorporated-companies-in-the-uk-october-to-december-2023</u></a> </p></authorialNote> <authorialNote marker="150"><p> The total register includes <u>all</u> companies required to file accounts with Companies House, whilst on the effective register companies in the course of dissolution are excluded from the count.</p></authorialNote> Therefore, at least 4.8 million companies will need to familiarise themselves with these changes. We do not consider the future cost to new companies. This is because the knowledge that companies will no longer need to hold a register centrally would be absorbed within the overall cost of incorporation.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>4.</num>
          <content>
            <p>At least one individual within each organisation will need to familiarise themselves with these new requirements. In most instances, it will be directors (and equivalents)/PSCs who will do this. We cost this as the opportunity cost of their time valued using the median hourly pay rate (excluding overtime) for managers, directors and senior officials from the Annual Survey of Hourly Earnings (ASHE) in 2023, uplifted by<b> </b>20% to account for non-wage labour costs.<authorialNote marker="151"><p> See: <a href="https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/earningsandworkinghours/datasets/occupation4digitsoc2010ashetable14"><u>https://www.ons.gov.uk/employmentandlabourmarket/peopleinwork/earningsandworkinghours/ datasets/occupation4digitsoc2010ashetable14</u></a><u> </u>  </p></authorialNote> <authorialNote marker="152"><p> Non-wage costs include sickness, maternity and paternity pay, National Insurance contributions and pension contributions.</p></authorialNote> Using the GDP deflator to bring this into 2019 prices, this is £25.20 per hour.<authorialNote marker="153"><p> See: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/gdp-deflators-at-market-prices-and-money-gdp"><u>https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/gdp-deflators-at-market-prices-and-money-gdp</u></a> </p></authorialNote> <authorialNote marker="154"><p> We use 2019 prices to align with the cost assessment produced in the primary legislation impact assessment</p></authorialNote></p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>8.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We envision that the familiarising process should be fairly quick and straightforward for companies. Engagement from Companies House suggests that there are a wide range of methods that can be used to make individuals aware of these changes (e.g. letters, emails, web pages etc.). However, Companies House will aim to use digital methods to make it easy and intuitive for companies to understand what is required of them. The familiarisation process should not require training of staff, changes to business processes or briefing sessions for entire teams.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>9.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Familiarisation will not require reading the regulations, Registrar’s rules or guidance, though may involve reading a letter or an email from Companies House. A message that covers an A4 page contains between 400-500 words, and the average reader can read at 200 words per minute. <authorialNote marker="155"><p> <a href="https://www.blackkitetranslations.com/quote/wordcount.php"><u>https://www.blackkitetranslations.com/quote/wordcount.php#:~:text=As%20a%20rule%20of%20thumb,average% 20400%20to%20500%20words</u></a>. </p></authorialNote> <authorialNote marker="156"><p> <a href="https://www.prsa.org/article/how-to-determine-average-reading-time"><u>https://www.prsa.org/article/how-to-determine-average-reading-time</u></a> </p></authorialNote> Overall, the process of familiarising with this policy change is unlikely to be very burdensome. However, taking into consideration that this is a new requirement and may take some additional time for individuals to fully understand – we have created three possible scenarios for familiarisation. </p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>5.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We envision that it would take individuals anywhere from ten (low) to thirty (high) minutes to understand the policy change - we use twenty minutes as our central estimate.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>6.</num>
          <content>
            <p>We estimate a central cost of £8.40 per entity, which translates to £40.3 million for all entities.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>7.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Table 1 outlines the estimated cost of familiarisation a) per entity and b) Overall for all entities:</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>Table 1: Estimated familiarisation cost </b></p>
            <table uk:widths="1.89in 1.73in 1.73in 1.73in">
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text" />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Low</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Central</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>High</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Cost per entity </b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£4.20</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£8.40</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£12.60</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Total Cost (All entities)</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£20,100,000</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£40,300,000</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£60,400,000</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>8.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Beyond familiarisation, we have not identified any further costs to business. They are still required to provide PSC information to Companies House, which they are doing currently – they just no longer need to keep this information locally as well.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
      <section eId="section_156">
        <heading>Benefits</heading>
        <intro>
          <p><b>Benefits</b></p>
        </intro>
        <paragraph>
          <num>9.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Keeping a local register involves a range of costs. Therefore, any costs a company will no longer need to incur from keeping a local register would be considered a cost saving/benefit.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>10.</num>
          <intro>
            <p>We identified the following benefits:</p>
          </intro>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><b>The cost of maintaining the register: </b>These costs will differ depending on the number of amendments that must be made to the register during a year.<b> </b>Internal data from Companies House shows the average number of PSC changes for all live companies on the register company is 0.38. Therefore, it is arguable that the cost per company to maintain a local PSC register was fairly low.<authorialNote marker="157"><p> See: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/5d431904e5274a699238cf8b/review-implementation-psc-register.pdf"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/5d431904e5274a699238cf8b/review-implementation-psc-register.pdf</u></a></p></authorialNote> Evidence from the PSC PIR suggests that the median cost of tasks related to the maintenance of information held on the PSC register since the initial submission of information was £2. This includes: checking information about PSCs, identifying new PSCs, collecting, collating and submitting information about new PSCs. <authorialNote marker="158"><p> Table 3.9 Overall cost of compliance with PSC regulations See: <a href="https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/5d431904e5274a699238cf8b/review-implementation-psc-register.pdf"><u>https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/media/5d431904e5274a699238cf8b/review-implementation-psc-register.pdf</u></a><u> </u></p></authorialNote> Entities will still need to complete these activities to submit the necessary information to Companies House, but will no longer be required for the purpose of maintaining a local register.</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><b>Requests to inspect the register: </b>Another cost where a person (either a member or a third party) makes a request to inspect the register. Since this information will be publicly available on the Companies House register, it is unlikely that companies will be contacted directly about their PSC register.</p>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
          <subparagraph>
            <num>•</num>
            <content>
              <p><b>Use of agents: </b>Where an agent is used, they will charge clients a fee – often to provide a package of services. We do not have any data on how many entities use agents nor the fees these agents charge. Therefore, we reference the evidence from the earlier LLP IA to inform our assumptions:<authorialNote marker="159"><p> The Companies and Limited Liability Partnerships (Filing Requirements) Regulations 2016 removed the requirement for LLPs to hold certain registers (of members, of members’ residential addresses, and the register of people with significant control) at either their registered office or an alternative specified location if the information is instead on the public register at Companies House. Given the similarities with this regulation and the changes being made in the PSC amendments – that an entity no longer has to keep a register locally as long as it’s held centrally - its analysis and findings are very relevant. See: <a href="https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2016/599/impacts"><u>https://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2016/599/impacts</u></a></p></authorialNote></p>
              <block name="embeddedStructure">
                <embeddedStructure>
                  <level>
                    <content>
                      <p><i>“We consider it is unlikely that LLPs which employ agents to undertake a package of entity services (including holding registers) […], we are unable to make an evidence-based assessment about the number of LLPs which would no longer use an agent as a result of the measure. We consider that it is unlikely that LLPs would use agents </i><i><u>only</u></i><i> to hold their registers; generally, holding registers will be part of a package of wider services.”</i></p>
                    </content>
                  </level>
                </embeddedStructure>
              </block>
            </content>
          </subparagraph>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>11.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Quantifying the scale of these benefits however is challenging due to the lack of available and comparable data. As a result, we use breakeven analysis to estimate the cost savings required.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>12.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Table 2 outlines the estimated minimum benefit/cost-savings required for entities to breakeven over a 10-year appraisal period:</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <content>
            <p><b>Table 2: Estimated annual benefit/cost-savings required </b></p>
            <table uk:widths="1.89in 1.73in 1.73in 1.73in">
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text" />
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Low</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Central</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>High</b></p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Savings per entity </b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£0.42</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£0.84</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£1.26</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text"><b>Total savings (All entities)</b></p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£2,015,000</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£4,030,000</p>
                </td>
                <td>
                  <p class="ia-table-text">£6,044,000</p>
                </td>
              </tr>
            </table>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
        <paragraph>
          <num>13.</num>
          <content>
            <p>Our central scenario estimates that the cost for businesses to familiarise with this change would be £40.3 million (see Table 1). If every company (4.8 million) were to save <u>at least</u> £0.84 per year from no longer holding a local register, over a 10-year appraisal period they would recoup their initial cost. Any cost savings beyond this would be considered the additional benefit to no longer holding a local register.</p>
          </content>
        </paragraph>
      </section>
